{"id":"e5d912b00ae0","content":"PortSwigger Lab Write-Up: DOM XSS in document.write Sink Using Source location.search Inside a Select Element\n\n3 min read\nJust now\n\n--\n\nDOM-based Cross-Site Scripting (DOM XSS) vulnerabilities occur when an application contains client-side JavaScript that processes data from an untrusted source (like the URL) in an unsafe way, usually by passing it to a dangerous “sink” function that renders content to the page.\nIn this write-up, we will analyze the script behavior, break down the context escaping required, and exploit a document.write sink inside a dropdown select element.\nLab Analysis & Vulnerability Identification\nThe target application features a product page with a stock checker dropdown. By inspecting the source code using the browser DevTools (as shown in your first image), we can locate the vulnerable code block responsible for rendering this element:\nJavaScript\nvar stores = [\"London\", \"Paris\", \"Milan\"];\nvar store = (new URLSearchParams(window.location.search)).get('storeId');\ndocument.write('<select name=\"storeId\">');\nif (store) {\ndocument.write('<option selected>' + store + '</option>');\n}\n// Loop that populates remaining store options...Breaking Down the Mechanics:\n\n• The Source: window.location.search. This pulls query parameters directly from the URL.\n\n• The Variable: The script creates a URLSearchParams object to read the value of the storeId query parameter. Whatever string is passed via ?storeId=XYZ populates the store variable.\n\n• The Sink: document.write(). This takes any string passed into it and evaluates it straight into the webpage's DOM.\nBecause the code inserts the raw, unsanitized store variable directly into a string inside document.write(), we control what gets written to the HTML document body.\nCrafting the Breakout Payload\nThe challenge lies in the exact position where our input lands. It gets wrapped directly inside an HTML structure:\nHTML\n<select name=\"storeId\">\n<option selected>[OUR INPUT HERE]</option>\n</select>If we just inject <script>alert(1)</script>, the browser interprets it as plain text content inside the <option> tag instead of treating it as executable code. To fix this, we need to manually close the open elements.\nThe Payload Structure:\nHTML\n\"></select><img src=1 onerror=alert(1)>\n• \">: Closes the attributes and the opening <option> tag itself.\n\n• </select>: Explicitly closes the parent <select> block. This forces the browser back into standard HTML parsing context.\n\n• <img src=1 onerror=alert(1)>: Instantiates an image element pointing to an invalid source (1). When it inevitably fails to load, it immediately executes the inline JavaScript inside the onerror event handler.\nExecution Steps\n\n• Open any product page within the lab instance.\n\n• Modify the URL query parameters in the address bar. Specifically, append or replace the storeId parameter value with your URL-encoded payload.\n\n• Hit enter to load the malicious URL:\n\n• Plaintext\nhttps://<YOUR-LAB-ID>.web-security-academy.net/product?productId=2&storeId=\"></select><img src=1 onerror=alert(1)>\n\n• The moment the client-side JavaScript reads the new URL parameters, it renders our closing tags, breaks out of the select block, and triggers the alert(1) popup box.\nImage References\nPress enter or click to view image in full size\n\nInspecting the DOM in DevTools reveals how the custom JavaScript uses document.write to dynamically construct the <select> store drop-down using the storeId URL query parameter.Press enter or click to view image in full size\n\nSuccessful XSS execution showing the JavaScript alert(1) box popping up after injecting the breakout payload into the URL parameter."}